{
  "texts": [
    "Another commonly used diffractive surface design approach relies on the difference between the refractive indices of the fabrication material (substrate), n surf ace and the light propagation medium, n medium, e.g., n medium = 1 in air.",
    "In general, the index contrast of a diffractive feature (with a height of h) with respect to the background induces an optical path delay in the form of Δφ = 2πh λ ðn surf ace À n medium Þ.",
    "Typically, diffractive surfaces fabricated using a single dielectric material have a constant n surf ace over their pixels, which requires the thickness of the fabrication material to be a function of space, i.e., hðx,yÞ, leading to a 2D transmission function, T x,y ð Þ= expðj 2πhðx,yÞ λ ðn surf ace À n medium ÞÞ (Fig. 3a).",
    "With the wide availability of additive manufacturing and nanofabrication techniques [43] [44] [45] [46], this approach has become one of the most commonly employed methods in implementing diffractive surfaces.",
    "An alternative method relies on the spatial engineering of the refractive index, i.e., n surf ace ðx,yÞ, while keeping h constant (shown in Fig. 3b) 47, 48."
  ]
}